</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="582F5F67985D98461D215BE45E40E451" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" type="notes">
<paragraph id="23C263EAC907E2C80E72442487AF4565" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6D907FAE6646FD966C047581653C075D" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">
Collections were made from the hindgut of 
<taxonomicName id="BA810F95016B698DA08BE0749AB7084A" authorityName="Kimmins" authorityYear="1941" class="Insecta" family="Nemouridae" genus="Protonemura" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Protonemura montana" order="Plecoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="montana">
<emphasis id="41FA7F2C95DEDF50FB187A8008FB9780" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Protonemura montana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Kimmins nymphs, with a low infestation rate (2%). 
<taxonomicName id="BE606106C3408E1764E220AFCCE6C9EF" authorityName="Leger &amp; Gauthier" authorityYear="1931" class="Kickxellomycetes" family="Orphellaceae" genus="Orphella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Orphella coronata" order="Orphellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Zygomycota" rank="species" species="coronata">
<emphasis id="C7777A881C8C9172384D503983382632" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Orphella coronata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been reported from diverse localities in Europe, (e.g. France (
<bibRefCitation id="73F142371E828043938705EE578D7550" author="Leger, L" journalOrPublisher="Travaux du Laboratoire d' Hydrobiologie et de Pisciculture de l'Universite de Grenoble" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="67 - 72" refId="B18" refString="Leger, L, Gauthier, M, 1931. Orphella coronata n. g., n. sp. Entophyte parasite des larves de Nemurides. Travaux du Laboratoire d' Hydrobiologie et de Pisciculture de l'Universite de Grenoble 23: 67 - 72" title="Orphella coronata n. g., n. sp. Entophyte parasite des larves de Nemurides." volume="23" year="1931">
<normalizedToken id="089CE6E821FAAC375B0163F346A32C6E" originalValue="Léger">Leger</normalizedToken>
and Gauthier 1931
</bibRefCitation>
, 1932), Norway (
<bibRefCitation id="A54C0BBF91EFEAACE3A587785A8118BE" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2005.11832936" author="White, MM" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="891 - 910" refId="B72" refString="White, MM, Lichtwardt, RW, 2004. Fungal symbionts (Harpellales) in Norwegian aquatic insect larvae. Mycologia 96: 891 - 910, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2005.11832936" title="Fungal symbionts (Harpellales) in Norwegian aquatic insect larvae." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2005.11832936" volume="96" year="2004">White and Lichtwardt 2004</bibRefCitation>
), Spain (
<bibRefCitation id="14864E2C2CA88C898C0145FAA6F602DA" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2006.11832740" author="Valle, LG" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="1335 - 1347" refId="B66" refString="Valle, LG, Santamaria, S, 2005. Zygospores as evidence of sexual reproduction in the genus Orphella. Mycologia 97: 1335 - 1347, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2006.11832740" title="Zygospores as evidence of sexual reproduction in the genus Orphella." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2006.11832740" volume="97" year="2005">Valle and Santamaria 2005</bibRefCitation>
), Portugal (
<bibRefCitation id="C233B50311B08B9860E946F2E3414F25" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/12-211" author="Valle, LG" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="748 - 759" refId="B59" refString="Valle, LG, 2013a. New and rare Harpellales from Portugal and northwestern Iberian Peninsula: discovering the hidden mycobiota of Galicia-Tras-os-Montes region. Mycologia 105: 748 - 759, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/12-211" title="New and rare Harpellales from Portugal and northwestern Iberian Peninsula: discovering the hidden mycobiota of Galicia-Tras-os-Montes region." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/12-211" volume="105" year="2013 a">Valle 2013a</bibRefCitation>
) and Italy (
<bibRefCitation id="23B37F5ACE34187D3109E5D5B321F03A" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/12-184" author="Valle, LG" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="712 - 727" refId="B67" refString="Valle, LG, Rossi, W, Santamaria, S, 2013. New species and new records of trichomycetes from Italy. Mycologia 105: 712 - 727, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/12-184" title="New species and new records of trichomycetes from Italy." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/12-184" volume="105" year="2013">Valle et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
)). 
<taxonomicName id="753A789944880D94DF57C3B8F983D3D1" authorityName="Leger &amp; Gauthier" authorityYear="1931" class="Kickxellomycetes" family="Orphellaceae" genus="Orphella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Orphella coronata" order="Orphellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Zygomycota" rank="species" species="coronata">
<emphasis id="91B8CE7165FB581F7CBAB0AB8B3321A4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Orphella coronata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be the rarest species of the genus in the Bulgarian streams surveyed, although many potential hosts were dissected from the Struma River. Fortunately, the only 
<taxonomicName id="3D61B19316F8E8A8B3A95C2AE087BBEC" authorityName="Kempny" authorityYear="1898" class="Insecta" family="Nemouridae" genus="Protonemura" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Protonemura" order="Plecoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F5FC178271985C6FA27958C350013FB3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">Protonemura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
infested specimen was carrying various mature thalli of 
<taxonomicName id="6447FB17DEEE78DE76C4698A63B1D1DC" genus="O." lsidName="O. coronata" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" rank="species" species="coronata">
<emphasis id="9A381964B944067EBA020D80B79362F5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">O. coronata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, so that we could observe trichospores and the typical heterothallically-formed helicoidal zygospores typical for the species, these being very important to discern and identify possible cryptic species (
<bibRefCitation id="D9AA04DABB3A9FB47385C353311A43EF" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2006.11832740" author="Valle, LG" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="1335 - 1347" refId="B66" refString="Valle, LG, Santamaria, S, 2005. Zygospores as evidence of sexual reproduction in the genus Orphella. Mycologia 97: 1335 - 1347, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2006.11832740" title="Zygospores as evidence of sexual reproduction in the genus Orphella." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/15572536.2006.11832740" volume="97" year="2005">Valle and Santamaria 2005</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="3F91F622D7578D0A5916A3BB442475AE" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/13-349" author="Valle, LG" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" pagination="589 - 606" refId="B68" refString="Valle, LG, Rossi, W, Santamaria, S, 2014. Orphella intropus (Kickxellomycotina), a new insect endosymbiont with an unusual perforating holdfast system and other trichomycetes from Italy. Mycologia 106: 589 - 606, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/13-349" title="Orphella intropus (Kickxellomycotina), a new insect endosymbiont with an unusual perforating holdfast system and other trichomycetes from Italy." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/13-349" volume="106" year="2014">Valle et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="C9F847B9F9610F057DF597BBC1D7DBF1" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.2018.1448198" author="White, MM" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="55" refId="B73" refString="White, MM, Valle, LG, Lichtwardt, RW, Siri, A, Strongman, DB, William, RT, Gause, WJ, Tretter, ED, 2018. New species and emendations of Orphella: taxonomic and phylogenetic reassessment of the genus to establish the Orphellales, for stonefly gut fungi with a twist. Mycologia 110(1): 147-178. https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.2018.1448198" title="New species and emendations of Orphella: taxonomic and phylogenetic reassessment of the genus to establish the Orphellales, for stonefly gut fungi with a twist. Mycologia 110 (1): 147 - 178." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00275514.2018.1448198" year="2018">White et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
). Bulgarian specimens show the typical thallus with a bifurcate basal cell and allantoid trichospores (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="893927B5A279CF274B1367D93D3B8D1C" captionStart="Figures 21–25" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 21 - 25. Various species of Orphellales. 21 Orphella catalaunica from Leuctridae nymphs, trichospores and accompanying cells 22, 23 Orphella coronata from Nemouridae nymphs 22 allantoid trichospores and accompanying cells 23 zygospores produced homothallically 24, 25 Orphella helicospora from Leuctridae nymphs: 24 homothallical zygospores and accompanying cells 25 basal cell and holdfast. Scale bars: 25 μm in all figures." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.67.52055.figures21-25" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/414543" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">22</figureCitation>
), measuring 36-41 
<normalizedToken id="0A109D088DC19D9711B4E15509C89BF4" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5.5-6.5 
<normalizedToken id="DFCAD9D40BF4FEC6C8FCD1D83C8277F7" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
in our collections, slightly smaller than previously reported (35-48 
<normalizedToken id="C8C8025F8919B1E41E1B60828A76964C" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6-7.5 
<normalizedToken id="9C15DE4931E74219A2C233DAAE0C630D" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
according to Valle &amp; Santamaria 2004). Terminal cell measures 22-25 
<normalizedToken id="81E56C745B501010E8F912A1397BA795" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-3.5 
<normalizedToken id="1F34E00D234C83093517EBA1E902CF97" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
. Zygospores (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="6824D772F321E1E5280C094FFA75F2FE" captionStart="Figures 21–25" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 21 - 25. Various species of Orphellales. 21 Orphella catalaunica from Leuctridae nymphs, trichospores and accompanying cells 22, 23 Orphella coronata from Nemouridae nymphs 22 allantoid trichospores and accompanying cells 23 zygospores produced homothallically 24, 25 Orphella helicospora from Leuctridae nymphs: 24 homothallical zygospores and accompanying cells 25 basal cell and holdfast. Scale bars: 25 μm in all figures." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.67.52055.figures21-25" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/414543" pageId="0" pageNumber="55">23</figureCitation>
) in our collections measure 26-32 
<normalizedToken id="A30B0A3A59C424C6C6163F8043E55E36" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6-7 
<normalizedToken id="18E7F3FAEF8340049CD61EB3A426CA67" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, also somewhat smaller than those reported in the description of the zygospores (30-35 
<normalizedToken id="9FEB92F35F0F32496B20491416FBE719" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-7 
<normalizedToken id="AADC534741C8232BDB807FA9EA8750D1" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
according to Valle &amp; Santamaria 2004), but likely attributable to intraspecific variation; in fact, just a couple of thalli were found producing sexual spores in our collections and about 5 producing trichospores.
</paragraph>
